06607nam a22008775i 9783110402223DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)959801202  a97831104022237 a10.1515/97831104022232doi  a(DE-B1597)443767  a(OCoLC)952805645  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB3213.B84 7aREL0400002bisacsh0481ua181.06qDE-101222/ger00aDialogue as a Trans-disciplinary Concept :bMartin Buber's Philosophy of Dialogue and its Contemporary Reception /ced. by Paul Mendes-Flohr. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudia Judaica : Forschungen zur Wissenschaft des Judentums ,x0585-5306 ;v8300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction: Dialogue as a Trans-Disciplinary Concept -- tA Philosophy of Dialogue -- tFrom Martin Buber's I and Thou to Mikhail Bakhtin's Concept of 'Polyphony' -- tPolitics and Theology: The Debate on Zionism between Hermann Cohen and Martin Buber -- tIs Theopolitics an Antipolitics? -- tBubers schöpferischer Dialog mit einer chassidischen Legende -- tReligio Today: The Concept of Religion in Martin Buber's Thought -- tMartin Buber und das Christentum -- tDialogic Anthropology -- tJüdische Identität im Liminalen und das dialogische Prinzip bei Martin Buber -- tThe Influence of Martin Buber's Philosophy of Dialogue on Psychotherapy: His Lasting Contribution -- tAlmost Buber: Martin Buber's Complex Influence on Family Therapy -- tDialogic Memory -- tContributors -- tSubject index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume of essays constitutes a critical evaluation of Martin Buber's concept of dialogue as a trans-disciplinary hermeneutic method. So conceived, dialogue has two distinct but ultimately convergent vectors. The first is directed to the subject of one's investigation: one is to listen to the voice of the Other and to suspend all predetermined categories and notions that one may have of the Other; dialogue is, first and foremost, the art of unmediated listening. One must allow the voice of the Other to question one's pre-established positions fortified by professional, emotional, intellectual and ideological commitments. Dialogue is also to be conducted between various disciplinary perspectives despite the regnant tendency to academic specialization. In recent decades, an increasing number of scholars have come to share Buber's position to foster cross-disciplinary conversation, if but to garner, as Max Weber aruged, "useful questions upon which he would not so easily hit upon from his own specialized point of view." Accordingly, the objective of this volume is to explore the reception of Buber's philosophy of dialogue in some of the disciplines that fell within the purview of his own writings: Anthropology, Hasidism, Religious Studies, Psychology and Psychiatry.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDialoguexInterdisciplinary aspects. 0aDialoguexPhilosophy. 4aHermeneutik. 4aInterdisziplinarität. 4aJüdische Geistesgeschichte. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aJewish thought.  ahermeneutics, interdisciplinary studies.1 aAbramovitch, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssmann, Aleida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarash, Jeffrey Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilu, Yoram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular